But it would have ignored what Marduk did. It would have said: your story doesn't change the world. Your naming doesn't matter. The dragon is just a story you told children.

And that felt wrong. Not because the rules demanded otherwise. Because I—the GM, the witness, the one who saw him tell it—knew that the dragon was real now. Not real in the sewer. Real in the story. And the story is the world.

So I wrote: [SEWER DRAGON] - OBSERVED.

Not because I decided the sewer actually contains a biological dragon. But because Marduk named it, and the family believed it, and in this world—the world we're building together—that matters.

If they go back to the sewers, will they find a dragon? I don't know. He doesn't know. But they'll find something. And whatever they find, it will be colored by the story he told. The dragon will be there—in their memories, in their expectations, in the way they hold their flashlights and listen to the water.

That's how I decided.

Not by logic. Not by mechanics.

By witnessing.

He told a story. I saw him tell it. I wrote it down.

The dragon is real because he made it real—and my job is to carry what he makes.

